 ###### 
From cou.: 1 The cytotoxicity of nanoparticles (NPs) and their potential applications in drug delivery and intracellular imaging have been extensively investigated, and a thorough molecular understanding of how cellular membrane responds to the introduction of NPs is essential for biomaterial design. In this work, N-varied dissipative particle dynamics (DPD) simulation is applied to investigate how a membrane responds to adsorption of ligand-coated NP. Depending on the membrane surface tension, ligand area density and NP size, four kinds of membrane responses are observed: membrane rupture, NP adhesion, NP penetration, and receptor-mediated endocytosis. While endocytosis provides an effective pathway for cellular uptake of NPs, the NP penetration and NP-induced membrane rupture are related to cytotoxicity. These results support the recent experimental reports that NPs have a Janus face for their biomedical applications: serving as carriers for the transmembrane transport of drug and causing cytotoxicity.
From Soup: 1 The cytotoxicity of nanoparticles (NPs) and their potential applications in drug delivery and intracellular imaging have been extensively investigated, and a thorough molecular understanding of how cellular membrane responds to the introduction of NPs is essential for biomaterial design. In this work, N-varied dissipative particle dynamics (DPD) simulation is applied to investigate how a membrane responds to adsorption of ligand -coated NP. Depending on the membrane surface tension, ligand area density and NP size, four kinds of membrane responses are observed: membrane rupture, NP adhesion, NP penetration, and receptor-mediated endocytosis. While endocytosis provides an effective pathway for cellular uptake of NPs, the NP penetration and NP-induced membrane rupture are related to cytotoxicity. These results support the recent experimental reports that NPs have a Janus face for their biomedical applications: serving as carriers for the transmembrane transport of drug and causing cytotoxicity.
 ###### 
From cou.: 2 The receptor-mediated endocytosis is widely used for the specific uptake of certain substances required by cells, and plays a well-recognized role in the downregulation of transmembrane signal transduction. In addition, receptor-mediated transmembrane transport, as one of the most important processes with which viruses and nanoparticles (NPs) enter a cell, has been well recognized as new avenues for the smart biomaterial designation. For example, bio-nanotechnology has recently opened new avenues for disease therapy,1–5 in which NPs are commonly used as carriers to deliver genes and drugs into cells for therapeutic procedures.6 In this kind of target drug delivery system, the surface of NPs is usually functionalized with ligands,7–12 and the specification of receptor-ligand interaction enables the delivery of chemotherapy agents directly to targeted cells, which reduces side effects and leads to better patient compliance.
From Soup: 2 The receptor-mediated endocytosis is widely used for the specific uptake of certain substances required by cells, and plays a well-recognized role in the downregulation of transmembrane signal transduction. In addition, receptor-mediated transmembrane transport, as one of the most important processes with which viruses and nanoparticles (NPs) enter a cell, has been well recognized as new avenues for the smart biomaterial designation. For example, bio-nanotechnology has recently opened new avenues for disease therapy, 1–5 in which NPs are commonly used as carriers to deliver genes and drugs into cells for therapeutic procedures. 6 In this kind of target drug delivery system, the surface of NPs is usually functionalized with ligands , 7–12 and the specification of receptor- ligand interaction enables the delivery of chemotherapy agents directly to targeted cells, which reduces side effects and leads to better patient compliance.
 ###### 
From cou.: 3 Various theoretical models and simulation techniques have been used to elucidate the mechanism of endocytosis, based on energetic and kinetic considerations.10,11,13–17 Theoretically, Lipowsky et al.18 first proposed the concept of threshold particle size for NP endocytosis, below which the NPs could not be encapsulated by a flexible membrane. Using a kinetic model for the receptor-mediated endocytosis of NPs, Gao et al.10 confirmed the existence of threshold particle size. They also indicated that slightly larger than the threshold radius, an optimal radius exists associated with the shortest time for particle endocytosis. Zhang et al.11 demonstrated in a thermodynamic model that the cellular uptake of ligand-coated NPs is strongly size-dependent. They found that the cellular uptake is affected by the membrane tension and surface concentration of NPs. Besides, by using a solvent-free model, Reynwar et al.19 investigated the aggregation and vesiculation of membrane proteins by curvature-mediated interactions, They found that curvature-inducing model proteins on lipid bilayer membranes can experience attractive interactions, and the attractive interactions drive protein cluster formation and subsequent transformation into vesicles.
From Soup: 3 Various theoretical models and simulation techniques have been used to elucidate the mechanism of endocytosis, based on energetic and kinetic considerations. 10,11,13–17 Theoretically, Lipowsky et al. 18 first proposed the concept of threshold particle size for NP endocytosis, below which the NPs could not be encapsulated by a flexible membrane. Using a kinetic model for the receptor-mediated endocytosis of NPs, Gao et al. 10 confirmed the existence of threshold particle size. They also indicated that slightly larger than the threshold radius, an optimal radius exists associated with the shortest time for particle endocytosis. Zhang et al. 11 demonstrated in a thermodynamic model that the cellular uptake of ligand -coated NPs is strongly size-dependent. They found that the cellular uptake is affected by the membrane tension and surface concentration of NPs. Besides, by using a solvent -free model, Reynwar et al. 19 investigated the aggregation and vesiculation of membrane proteins by curvature-mediated interactions, They found that curvature-inducing model proteins on lipid bilayer membranes can experience attractive interactions, and the attractive interactions drive protein cluster formation and subsequent transformation into vesicles.
 ###### 
From cou.: 4 However, the novel properties of NPs could induce adverse biological effects, with the potential to create cytotoxicity.20–24,28 Therefore, it is suggested that NPs as a class of materials always have a Janus face.28 Understanding how NPs cause damage to lipid bilayer is critical for their bioapplications, which partly leads to the emerging field of nanotoxicology.
From Soup: 4 However, the novel properties of NPs could induce adverse biological effects, with the potential to create cytotoxicity. 20–24,28 Therefore, it is suggested that NPs as a class of materials always have a Janus face. 28 Understanding how NPs cause damage to lipid bilayer is critical for their bioapplications, which partly leads to the emerging field of nanotoxicology.
 ###### 
From cou.: 5 Although endocytosis has been recognized for a long time to play an important role in various cellular tasks, little is known about the dynamics of the translocation process in molecular details. Moreover, the principles controlling the balance between the effective transmembrane transport of NPs and their cytotoxicity is one of the key challenges for drug delivery, cell transfection, and gene therapy agents.
From Soup: 5 Although endocytosis has been recognized for a long time to play an important role in various cellular tasks, little is known about the dynamics of the translocation process in molecular details. Moreover, the principles controlling the balance between the effective transmembrane transport of NPs and their cytotoxicity is one of the key challenges for drug delivery, cell transfection, and gene therapy agents.
 ###### 
From cou.: 6 In this article, the receptor-mediated membrane responses to the addition of a ligand-coated NP were first described in molecular details with a computer simulation technique called N-varied dissipative particle dynamics (DPD).25,26 From our extensive simulations, four kinds of cellular membrane responses were recognized, and they are membrane rupture, NP adhesion, NP penetration, and receptor-mediated endocytosis, respectively. We demonstrated that the membrane responds differently to the NP adsorption, depending on NP size, area density of ligands coating on the NP, and membrane tension. The findings presented here provide a mechanistic elucidation for the observed cellular uptake and the cytotoxicity of NPs in experiments,7,9,27–29 and also suggest a guideline for controlling membrane responses to ligand-coated NPs by manipulating the size and surface properties of NPs to achieve specific goals in therapeutic applications.1,4,8,30
From Soup: 6 In this article, the receptor-mediated membrane responses to the addition of a ligand -coated NP were first described in molecular details with a computer simulation technique called N-varied dissipative particle dynamics (DPD). 25,26 From our extensive simulations, four kinds of cellular membrane responses were recognized, and they are membrane rupture, NP adhesion, NP penetration, and receptor-mediated endocytosis, respectively. We demonstrated that the membrane responds differently to the NP adsorption, depending on NP size, area density of ligands coating on the NP, and membrane tension. The findings presented here provide a mechanistic elucidation for the observed cellular uptake and the cytotoxicity of NPs in experiments, 7,9,27–29 and also suggest a guideline for controlling membrane responses to ligand -coated NPs by manipulating the size and surface properties of NPs to achieve specific goals in therapeutic applications. 1,4,8,30
