From cou.: 8 The dissipative particle dynamics (DPD) method was first introduced to simulate the hydrodynamic behavior of complex fluids,36–38 and proved to be especially useful in studying the mesoscale behaviors of lipid bilayer membranes.39–42 The elementary units of DPD simulations are soft beads whose dynamics are governed by Newton's equation of motion, in a similar way as molecular dynamics method. The inter-bead force exerted on beads is composed of conservative, dissipative, and random forces. The conservative force between beads i and j, which is soft repulsive, is determined by
